modules.name: AWS.CodeCommit
modules.comments:
AWS CodeCommit

This is the AWS CodeCommit API Reference. This reference provides descriptions of the operations and data types for AWS CodeCommit API along with usage examples.

You can use the AWS CodeCommit API to work with the following objects:

Repositories, by calling the following:

  • BatchGetRepositories, which returns information about one or more repositories associated with your AWS account.

  • CreateRepository, which creates an AWS CodeCommit repository.

  • DeleteRepository, which deletes an AWS CodeCommit repository.

  • GetRepository, which returns information about a specified repository.

  • ListRepositories, which lists all AWS CodeCommit repositories associated with your AWS account.

  • UpdateRepositoryDescription, which sets or updates the description of the repository.

  • UpdateRepositoryName, which changes the name of the repository. If you change the name of a repository, no other users of that repository will be able to access it until you send them the new HTTPS or SSH URL to use.

Branches, by calling the following:

  • CreateBranch, which creates a new branch in a specified repository.

  • DeleteBranch, which deletes the specified branch in a repository unless it is the default branch.

  • GetBranch, which returns information about a specified branch.

  • ListBranches, which lists all branches for a specified repository.

  • UpdateDefaultBranch, which changes the default branch for a repository.

Files, by calling the following:

  • PutFile, which adds or modifies a file in a specified repository and branch.

Information about committed code in a repository, by calling the following:

  • GetBlob, which returns the base-64 encoded content of an individual Git blob object within a repository.

  • GetCommit, which returns information about a commit, including commit messages and author and committer information.

  • GetDifferences, which returns information about the differences in a valid commit specifier (such as a branch, tag, HEAD, commit ID or other fully qualified reference).

Pull requests, by calling the following:

  • CreatePullRequest, which creates a pull request in a specified repository.

  • DescribePullRequestEvents, which returns information about one or more pull request events.

  • GetCommentsForPullRequest, which returns information about comments on a specified pull request.

  • GetMergeConflicts, which returns information about merge conflicts between the source and destination branch in a pull request.

  • GetPullRequest, which returns information about a specified pull request.

  • ListPullRequests, which lists all pull requests for a repository.

  • MergePullRequestByFastForward, which merges the source destination branch of a pull request into the specified destination branch for that pull request using the fast-forward merge option.

  • PostCommentForPullRequest, which posts a comment to a pull request at the specified line, file, or request.

  • UpdatePullRequestDescription, which updates the description of a pull request.

  • UpdatePullRequestStatus, which updates the status of a pull request.

  • UpdatePullRequestTitle, which updates the title of a pull request.

Information about comments in a repository, by calling the following:

  • DeleteCommentContent, which deletes the content of a comment on a commit in a repository.

  • GetComment, which returns information about a comment on a commit.

  • GetCommentsForComparedCommit, which returns information about comments on the comparison between two commit specifiers in a repository.

  • PostCommentForComparedCommit, which creates a comment on the comparison between two commit specifiers in a repository.

  • PostCommentReply, which creates a reply to a comment.

  • UpdateComment, which updates the content of a comment on a commit in a repository.

Triggers, by calling the following:

  • GetRepositoryTriggers, which returns information about triggers configured for a repository.

  • PutRepositoryTriggers, which replaces all triggers for a repository and can be used to create or delete triggers.

  • TestRepositoryTriggers, which tests the functionality of a repository trigger by sending data to the trigger target.

For information about how to use AWS CodeCommit, see the AWS CodeCommit User Guide.

declarations.comments:
Returns information about one or more repositories.

The description field for a repository accepts all HTML characters and all valid Unicode characters. Applications that do not HTML-encode the description and display it in a web page could expose users to potentially malicious code. Make sure that you HTML-encode the description field in any application that uses this API to display the repository description on a web page.
declarations.title: batchGetRepositories

declarations.comments:
Creates a new branch in a repository and points the branch to a commit.

Calling the create branch operation does not set a repository's default branch. To do this, call the update default branch operation.
declarations.title: createBranch

declarations.comments: Creates a pull request in the specified repository.
declarations.title: createPullRequest

declarations.comments: Creates a new, empty repository.
declarations.title: createRepository

declarations.comments: Deletes a branch from a repository, unless that branch is the default branch for the repository.
declarations.title: deleteBranch

declarations.comments: Deletes the content of a comment made on a change, file, or commit in a repository.
declarations.title: deleteCommentContent

declarations.comments:
Deletes a repository. If a specified repository was already deleted, a null repository ID will be returned.

Deleting a repository also deletes all associated objects and metadata. After a repository is deleted, all future push calls to the deleted repository will fail.
declarations.title: deleteRepository

declarations.comments: Returns information about one or more pull request events.
declarations.title: describePullRequestEvents

declarations.comments: Returns the base-64 encoded content of an individual blob within a repository.
declarations.title: getBlob

declarations.comments: Returns information about a repository branch, including its name and the last commit ID.
declarations.title: getBranch

declarations.comments: Returns the content of a comment made on a change, file, or commit in a repository.
declarations.title: getComment

declarations.comments: Returns information about comments made on the comparison between two commits.
declarations.title: getCommentsForComparedCommit

declarations.comments: Returns comments made on a pull request.
declarations.title: getCommentsForPullRequest

declarations.comments: Returns information about a commit, including commit message and committer information.
declarations.title: getCommit

declarations.comments: Returns information about the differences in a valid commit specifier (such as a branch, tag, HEAD, commit ID or other fully qualified reference). Results can be limited to a specified path.
declarations.title: getDifferences

declarations.comments: Returns information about merge conflicts between the before and after commit IDs for a pull request in a repository.
declarations.title: getMergeConflicts

declarations.comments: Gets information about a pull request in a specified repository.
declarations.title: getPullRequest

declarations.comments:
Returns information about a repository.

The description field for a repository accepts all HTML characters and all valid Unicode characters. Applications that do not HTML-encode the description and display it in a web page could expose users to potentially malicious code. Make sure that you HTML-encode the description field in any application that uses this API to display the repository description on a web page.
declarations.title: getRepository

declarations.comments: Gets information about triggers configured for a repository.
declarations.title: getRepositoryTriggers

declarations.comments: Gets information about one or more branches in a repository.
declarations.title: listBranches

declarations.comments: Returns a list of pull requests for a specified repository. The return list can be refined by pull request status or pull request author ARN.
declarations.title: listPullRequests

declarations.comments: Gets information about one or more repositories.
declarations.title: listRepositories

declarations.comments: Closes a pull request and attempts to merge the source commit of a pull request into the specified destination branch for that pull request at the specified commit using the fast-forward merge option.
declarations.title: mergePullRequestByFastForward

declarations.comments: Posts a comment on the comparison between two commits.
declarations.title: postCommentForComparedCommit

declarations.comments: Posts a comment on a pull request.
declarations.title: postCommentForPullRequest

declarations.comments: Posts a comment in reply to an existing comment on a comparison between commits or a pull request.
declarations.title: postCommentReply

declarations.comments: Adds or updates a file in an AWS CodeCommit repository.
declarations.title: putFile

declarations.comments: Replaces all triggers for a repository. This can be used to create or delete triggers.
declarations.title: putRepositoryTriggers

declarations.comments: Tests the functionality of repository triggers by sending information to the trigger target. If real data is available in the repository, the test will send data from the last commit. If no data is available, sample data will be generated.
declarations.title: testRepositoryTriggers

declarations.comments: Replaces the contents of a comment.
declarations.title: updateComment

declarations.comments:
Sets or changes the default branch name for the specified repository.

If you use this operation to change the default branch name to the current default branch name, a success message is returned even though the default branch did not change.
declarations.title: updateDefaultBranch

declarations.comments: Replaces the contents of the description of a pull request.
declarations.title: updatePullRequestDescription

declarations.comments: Updates the status of a pull request.
declarations.title: updatePullRequestStatus

declarations.comments: Replaces the title of a pull request.
declarations.title: updatePullRequestTitle

declarations.comments:
Sets or changes the comment or description for a repository.

The description field for a repository accepts all HTML characters and all valid Unicode characters. Applications that do not HTML-encode the description and display it in a web page could expose users to potentially malicious code. Make sure that you HTML-encode the description field in any application that uses this API to display the repository description on a web page.
declarations.title: updateRepositoryDescription

declarations.comments: Renames a repository. The repository name must be unique across the calling AWS account. In addition, repository names are limited to 100 alphanumeric, dash, and underscore characters, and cannot include certain characters. The suffix ".git" is prohibited. For a full description of the limits on repository names, see Limits in the AWS CodeCommit User Guide.
declarations.title: updateRepositoryName

A client request token is an unique, client-generated idempotency token that when provided in a request, ensures the request cannot be repeated with a changed parameter. If a request is received with the same parameters and a token is included, the request will return information about the initial request that used that token.

declarations.comments: The specified blob is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidBlobIdException

declarations.comments: The specified reference name is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidBranchNameException

declarations.comments: The client request token is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidClientRequestTokenException

declarations.comments: The comment ID is not in a valid format. Make sure that you have provided the full comment ID.
declarations.title: InvalidCommentIdException

declarations.comments: The specified commit is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidCommitException

declarations.comments: The specified commit ID is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidCommitIdException

declarations.comments: The specified continuation token is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidContinuationTokenException

declarations.comments: The pull request description is not valid. Descriptions are limited to 1,000 characters in length.
declarations.title: InvalidDescriptionException

declarations.comments: The destination commit specifier is not valid. You must provide a valid branch name, tag, or full commit ID.
declarations.title: InvalidDestinationCommitSpecifierException

declarations.comments: The specified email address either contains one or more characters that are not allowed, or it exceeds the maximum number of characters allowed for an email address.
declarations.title: InvalidEmailException

declarations.comments: The location of the file is not valid. Make sure that you include the extension of the file as well as the file name.
declarations.title: InvalidFileLocationException

declarations.comments: The specified file mode permission is not valid. For a list of valid file mode permissions, see PutFile.
declarations.title: InvalidFileModeException

declarations.comments: The position is not valid. Make sure that the line number exists in the version of the file you want to comment on.
declarations.title: InvalidFilePositionException

declarations.comments: The specified number of maximum results is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidMaxResultsException

declarations.comments: The specified merge option is not valid. The only valid value is FAST_FORWARD_MERGE.
declarations.title: InvalidMergeOptionException

declarations.comments: The specified sort order is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidOrderException

declarations.comments: The parent commit ID is not valid. The commit ID cannot be empty, and must match the head commit ID for the branch of the repository where you want to add or update a file.

declarations.comments: The specified path is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidPathException

declarations.comments: The pull request event type is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidPullRequestEventTypeException

declarations.comments: The pull request ID is not valid. Make sure that you have provided the full ID and that the pull request is in the specified repository, and then try again.
declarations.title: InvalidPullRequestIdException

declarations.comments: The pull request status is not valid. The only valid values are OPEN and CLOSED.
declarations.title: InvalidPullRequestStatusException

declarations.comments: The pull request status update is not valid. The only valid update is from OPEN to CLOSED.
declarations.title: InvalidPullRequestStatusUpdateException

declarations.comments: The specified reference name format is not valid. Reference names must conform to the Git references format, for example refs/heads/master. For more information, see Git Internals - Git References or consult your Git documentation.

declarations.comments: Either the enum is not in a valid format, or the specified file version enum is not valid in respect to the current file version.
declarations.title: InvalidRelativeFileVersionEnumException

declarations.comments: The specified repository description is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryDescriptionException

declarations.comments:
At least one specified repository name is not valid.

This exception only occurs when a specified repository name is not valid. Other exceptions occur when a required repository parameter is missing, or when a specified repository does not exist.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryNameException

declarations.comments: One or more branch names specified for the trigger is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryTriggerBranchNameException

declarations.comments: The custom data provided for the trigger is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryTriggerCustomDataException

declarations.comments: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) for the trigger is not valid for the specified destination. The most common reason for this error is that the ARN does not meet the requirements for the service type.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryTriggerDestinationArnException

declarations.comments: One or more events specified for the trigger is not valid. Check to make sure that all events specified match the requirements for allowed events.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryTriggerEventsException

declarations.comments: The name of the trigger is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryTriggerNameException

declarations.comments: The region for the trigger target does not match the region for the repository. Triggers must be created in the same region as the target for the trigger.
declarations.title: InvalidRepositoryTriggerRegionException

declarations.comments: The specified sort by value is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidSortByException

declarations.comments: The source commit specifier is not valid. You must provide a valid branch name, tag, or full commit ID.
declarations.title: InvalidSourceCommitSpecifierException

declarations.comments: The target for the pull request is not valid. A target must contain the full values for the repository name, source branch, and destination branch for the pull request.
declarations.title: InvalidTargetException

declarations.comments: The targets for the pull request is not valid or not in a valid format. Targets are a list of target objects. Each target object must contain the full values for the repository name, source branch, and destination branch for a pull request.
declarations.title: InvalidTargetsException

declarations.comments: The title of the pull request is not valid. Pull request titles cannot exceed 100 characters in length.

declarations.comments: The file name is not valid because it has exceeded the character limit for file names. File names, including the path to the file, cannot exceed the character limit.
declarations.title: NameLengthExceededException

declarations.comments: The parent commit ID is not valid. The specified parent commit ID does not exist in the specified branch of the repository.
